Details
1. Enabling ESM in Node.js
- Use .mjs extension OR package.json with "type": "module" OR CLI flag --input-type=module. Conversely, use .cjs or "type":"commonjs" for CommonJS.

2. Import specifier types and mandatory file extensions
- Relative specifiers (./foo.js) must include the extension; directory index imports must explicitly reference the file (./dir/index.js).
- Bare specifiers resolve via Node package resolution and obey package.json exports mapping when present; if exports is absent, path fallback to package main applies.

3. import() and import.meta APIs
- Dynamic import: import(specifier) returns Promise<ModuleNamespace>.
- import.meta.url: string file: URL of the current module.
- import.meta.resolve(specifier): returns absolute URL string that specifier would resolve to; synchronous API in modern Node.
- import.meta.filename and import.meta.dirname: provide filesystem paths analogous to __filename and __dirname (file: modules only).

4. Interaction with CommonJS
- Importing CJS yields namespace object: { default: module.exports, 'module.exports': module.exports, ...detectedNamedExports }.
- Named exports detection is best-effort via static analysis; live-binding updates to module.exports are not reflected in detected named exports after CJS evaluation.
- To require inside ESM: const require = module.createRequire(import.meta.url).

5. Packages, exports field, and resolution
- package.json "exports" restricts what internal paths can be imported via bare specifiers; bare specifiers without explicit file extension are allowed only for packages without exports or when mapping exists.

6. Implementation notes and pitfalls
- Always include file extension in relative imports to avoid resolution errors in Node and browsers.
- Use import.meta.url + new URL('./file', import.meta.url) to compute file-based resource paths robustly.
- Beware of duplicated module loads when specifiers differ by query/fragment; modules are cached by resolved URL including query/fragment.

Supplementary details
- Performance: importing built-in modules as ESM may signal initialization of all named exports up-front; for performance-sensitive code, require() may lazily populate exports in CommonJS contexts.
- Testing: validate both ESM and CJS entrypoints; use module.createRequire() where native CJS behavior is required.

Reference details (exact APIs and signatures)
- import(specifier: string | URL) -> Promise<ModuleNamespace>
- import.meta.url -> string (file: URL of current module)
- import.meta.resolve(specifier: string, parentURL?: string | URL) -> string (absolute URL) — synchronous
- module.createRequire(filename: string | URL) -> function require(path)
- package.json: "type": "module" | "commonjs"; "exports": mapping object to control package entry points

